ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon dots (CDs) have emerged as a novel material that combines the properties of traditional quantum dots (TQDs) and carbon-based substances in the past few years. [1] In contrast, CDs have numerous advantageous properties including water solubility, excellent fluorescent properties, good biocompatibility, low toxicity, and inexpensive scale-up production.[2] Consequently, there has been an increased focus on the production of CDs and their utilization in the fields of chemistry and related sciences. [3]
                     . Currently, CDs have been successfully applied in various fields such as bio-imaging [4], biomarker detection [5], intelligent detection [6], photocatalysis [7], anti-counterfeiting [8], and optoelectronic devices [9]. Due to the fluorescent characteristics of CDs and the ample number of functional groups on their surface, chemical sensing is one of their most promising applications. [10–12] Various sustainable and organic materials can be utilized to create eco-friendly CDs, with simple manufacturing methods. [13,14]. This work adopted a one-step hydrothermal synthetic strategy for preparing B-CDs from a bird's nest, a natural and green carbon source (Fig. 1.
                     ). Bird's nest is a natural biomass with salivary acids, water-soluble proteins, and carbohydrates as its main components. Under high temperatures and pressure, this raw material can form natural N-element-doped CDs. Compared to organic reagent synthesis, the hydrothermal synthesis method utilizing a bird's nest as a raw material is not only convenient but also aligns with the principles of green chemistry development. Additionally, it exhibits excellent biocompatibility [15].
